[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] This is a property of a system—whether a program, computer, or a network—where there is a separate execution point or "thread of control" for each process.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] A *concurrent system* is one where a computation can advance without waiting for all other computations to complete.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing is a form of modular programming.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] In its paradigm an overall computation is factored into subcomputations that may be executed concurrently.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Pioneers in the field of concurrent computing include Edsger Dijkstra, Per Brinch Hansen, and C.A.R.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] The concept of concurrent computing is frequently confused with the related but distinct concept of parallel computing, although both can be described as "multiple processes executing *during the same period of time*".
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] By contrast, concurrent computing consists of process *lifetimes* overlapping, but execution does not happen at the same instant.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] The goal here is to model processes that happen concurrently, like multiple clients accessing a server at the same time.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Structuring software systems as composed of multiple concurrent, communicating parts can be useful for tackling complexity, regardless of whether the parts can be executed in parallel.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] In this way, multiple processes are part-way through execution at a single instant, but only one process is being executed at that instant.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computations *may* be executed in parallel, for example, by assigning each process to a separate processor or processor core, or distributing a computation across a network.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] The exact timing of when tasks in a concurrent system are executed depends on the scheduling, and tasks need not always be executed concurrently.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] The word "sequential" is used as an antonym for both "concurrent" and "parallel"; when these are explicitly distinguished, *concurrent/sequential* and *parallel/serial* are used as opposing pairs.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] A schedule in which tasks execute one at a time (serially, no parallelism), without interleaving (sequentially, no concurrency: no task begins until the prior task ends) is called a *serial schedule*.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] A set of tasks that can be scheduled serially is *serializable*, which simplifies concurrency control.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] The main challenge in designing concurrent programs is concurrency control: ensuring the correct sequencing of the interactions or communications between different computational executions, and coordinating access to resources that are shared among executions.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Potential problems include race conditions, deadlocks, and resource starvation.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Suppose `balance = 500`, and two concurrent *threads* make the calls `withdraw(300)` and `withdraw(350)`.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] If line 3 in both operations executes before line 5 both operations will find that `balance >= withdrawal` evaluates to `true`, and execution will proceed to subtracting the withdrawal amount.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] However, since both processes perform their withdrawals, the total amount withdrawn will end up being more than the original balance.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] These sorts of problems with shared resources benefit from the use of concurrency control, or non-blocking algorithms.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Introduced in 1962, Petri nets were an early attempt to codify the rules of concurrent execution.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Dataflow theory later built upon these, and Dataflow architectures were created to physically implement the ideas of dataflow theory.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Beginning in the late 1970s, process calculi such as Calculus of Communicating Systems (CCS) and Communicating Sequential Processes (CSP) were developed to permit algebraic reasoning about systems composed of interacting components.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] The π-calculus added the capability for reasoning about dynamic topologies.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Input/output automata were introduced in 1987.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Logics such as Lamport's TLA+, and mathematical models such as traces and Actor event diagrams, have also been developed to describe the behavior of concurrent systems.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Software transactional memory borrows from database theory the concept of atomic transactions and applies them to memory accesses.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages and multiprocessor programs must have a consistency model (also known as a memory model).
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] The consistency model defines rules for how operations on computer memory occur and how results are produced.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] One of the first consistency models was Leslie Lamport's sequential consistency model.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Sequential consistency is the property of a program that its execution produces the same results as a sequential program.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Specifically, a program is sequentially consistent if "the results of any execution is the same as if the operations of all the processors were executed in some sequential order, and the operations of each individual processor appear in this sequence in the order specified by its program".
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] A number of different methods can be used to implement concurrent programs, such as implementing each computational execution as an operating system process, or implementing the computational processes as a set of threads within a single operating system process.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] In some concurrent computing systems, communication between the concurrent components is hidden from the programmer (e.g., by using futures), while in others it must be handled explicitly.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] The exchange of messages may be carried out asynchronously, or may use a synchronous "rendezvous" style in which the sender blocks until the message is received.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Asynchronous message passing may be reliable or unreliable (sometimes referred to as "send and pray").
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Message-passing concurrency tends to be far easier to reason about than shared-memory concurrency, and is typically considered a more robust form of concurrent programming.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Shared memory and message passing concurrency have different performance characteristics.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Typically (although not always), the per-process memory overhead and task switching overhead is lower in a message passing system, but the overhead of message passing is greater than for a procedure call.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] These differences are often overwhelmed by other performance factors.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent computing developed out of earlier work on railroads and telegraphy, from the 19th and early 20th century, and some terms date to this period, such as semaphores.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] These arose to address the question of how to handle multiple trains on the same railroad system (avoiding collisions and maximizing efficiency) and how to handle multiple transmissions over a given set of wires (improving efficiency), such as via time-division multiplexing (1870s).
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] The academic study of concurrent algorithms started in the 1960s, with Dijkstra (1965) credited with being the first paper in this field, identifying and solving mutual exclusion.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrency is pervasive in computing, occurring from low-level hardware on a single chip to worldwide networks.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] At the network level, networked systems are generally concurrent by their nature, as they consist of separate devices.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Concurrent programming languages are programming languages that use language constructs for concurrency.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] These constructs may involve multi-threading, support for distributed computing, message passing, shared resources (including shared memory) or futures and promises.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Such languages are sometimes described as *concurrency-oriented languages* or *concurrency-oriented programming languages* (COPL).
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Today, the most commonly used programming languages that have specific constructs for concurrency are Java and C#.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Both of these languages fundamentally use a shared-memory concurrency model, with locking provided by monitors (although message-passing models can and have been implemented on top of the underlying shared-memory model).
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Of the languages that use a message-passing concurrency model, Erlang was probably the most widely used in industry as of 2010.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Many concurrent programming languages have been developed more as research languages (e.g., Pict) rather than as languages for production use.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] However, languages such as Erlang, Limbo, and occam have seen industrial use at various times in the last 20 years.
[src:fortress-language/concurrent-computing] Many other languages provide support for concurrency in the form of libraries, at levels roughly comparable with the above list.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] The language was not designed to be similar to Fortran.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] Syntactically, it most resembles Scala, Standard ML, and Haskell.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] Fortress was designed from the outset to have multiple syntactic stylesheets.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] Source code can be rendered as ASCII text, in Unicode, or as a prettied image.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] This would allow for support of mathematical symbols and other symbols in the rendered output for easier reading.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] An emacs-based tool named *fortify* transforms ASCII-based Fortress source code into LaTeX output.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] Fortress was also designed to be both highly parallel and have rich functionality contained within libraries, drawing from Java.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] For example, the `for` loop construct was a parallel operation, which would not necessarily iterate in a strictly linear manner, depending on the underlying implementation.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] However, the `for` construct was a library function and could be replaced by another version of the programmer's liking rather than being built into the language.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] Then they made the compiler trying to maintain a one-to-one correspondence between pseudocode and executable Fortress.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] Fortress was one of three languages created with funding from the High Productivity Computing Systems project; the others were X10 from IBM and Chapel from Cray, Inc.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] In November 2006, when DARPA approved funding for the third phase of the HPCS project, X10 and Chapel were funded, but Fortress was not, leading to uncertainty about the future of Fortress.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] In January 2007, Fortress was released as open-source.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] Version 1.0 of the Fortress Language Specification was released in April 2008, along with a compliant implementation targeting the Java virtual machine.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] In July 2012, Steele announced that active development on Fortress would cease after a brief winding-down period, citing complications with using Fortress's type system on existing virtual machines.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] The *export* statement makes the program executable and every executable program in Fortress must implement the *run()* function.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] The file where the program is saved for compilation must have the same name as the one specified in the initial *component* statement.
[src:fortress-language/fortress-programming-language] The *println()* function is what outputs the "Hello, World!" words on the screen.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Generic programming was introduced to the mainstream with Ada in 1977.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] With templates in C++, generic programming became part of the repertoire of professional library design.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The techniques were further improved and *parameterized types* were introduced in the influential 1994 book *Design Patterns*.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] New techniques were introduced by Andrei Alexandrescu in his 2001 book *Modern C++ Design: Generic Programming and Design Patterns Applied*.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Subsequently, D implemented the same ideas.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Such software entities are known as *generics* in Ada, C#, Delphi, Eiffel, F#, Java, Mojo, Nim, Python, Go, Rust, Swift, TypeScript, and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] They are known as *parametric polymorphism* in ML, Scala, Julia, and Haskell.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The "generic programming" paradigm is an approach to software decomposition whereby fundamental requirements on types are abstracted from across concrete examples of algorithms and data structures and formalized as concepts, analogously to the abstraction of algebraic theories in abstract algebra.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Early examples of this programming approach were implemented in Scheme and Ada, although the best known example is the Standard Template Library (STL), which developed a theory of iterators that is used to decouple sequence data structures and the algorithms operating on them.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For example, given *N* sequence data structures, e.g. singly linked list, vector etc., and *M* algorithms to operate on them, e.g.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] `find`, `sort` etc., a direct approach would implement each algorithm specifically for each data structure, giving *N* × *M* combinations to implement.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Thus, only *N* + *M* data structure-algorithm combinations need be implemented.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] An important point is that a data structure will return a model of the most general concept that can be implemented efficiently—computational complexity requirements are explicitly part of the concept definition.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This limits the data structures a given algorithm can be applied to and such complexity requirements are a major determinant of data structure choice.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Generic programming similarly has been applied in other domains, e.g. graph algorithms.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Although this approach often uses language features of compile-time genericity and templates, it is independent of particular language-technical details.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] — Alexander Stepanov, An Interview with A.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Other programming paradigms that have been described as generic programming include *Datatype generic programming* as described in "Generic Programming – an Introduction".
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The *Scrap your boilerplate* approach is a lightweight generic programming approach for Haskell.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] In this article we distinguish the high-level programming paradigms of *generic programming*, above, from the lower-level programming language *genericity mechanisms* used to implement them (see Programming language support for genericity).
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For further discussion and comparison of generic programming paradigms, see.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Genericity facilities have existed in high-level languages since at least the 1970s in languages such as ML, CLU and Ada, and were subsequently adopted by many object-based and object-oriented languages, including BETA, C++, D, Eiffel, Java, and DEC's now defunct Trellis-Owl.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Genericity is implemented and supported differently in various programming languages; the term "generic" has also been used differently in various programming contexts.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For example, in Forth the compiler can execute code while compiling and one can create new *compiler keywords* and new implementations for those words on the fly.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] It has few *words* that expose the compiler behaviour and therefore naturally offers *genericity* capacities that, however, are not referred to as such in most Forth texts.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The term has been used in functional programming, specifically in Haskell-like languages, which use a structural type system where types are always parametric and the actual code on those types is generic.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] These uses still serve a similar purpose of code-saving and rendering an abstraction.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Arrays and structs can be viewed as predefined generic types.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Every usage of an array or struct type instantiates a new concrete type, or reuses a previous instantiated type.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Array element types and struct element types are parameterized types, which are used to instantiate the corresponding generic type.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] All this is usually built-in in the compiler and the syntax differs from other generic constructs.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Some extensible programming languages try to unify built-in and user defined generic types.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A broad survey of genericity mechanisms in programming languages follows.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For a specific survey comparing suitability of mechanisms for generic programming, see.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] When creating container classes in statically typed languages, it is inconvenient to write specific implementations for each datatype contained, especially if the code for each datatype is virtually identical.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Above, `T` is a placeholder for whatever type is specified when the list is created.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] These "generic objects of type `T`", commonly called templates, allow a class to be reused with different datatypes as long as certain contracts such as subtypes and signature are kept.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This genericity mechanism should not be confused with *inclusion polymorphism*, which is the algorithmic usage of exchangeable sub-classes: for instance, a list of objects of type `MovingEntity` containing objects of type `Animal` and `Car`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The C++ `template` construct used above is widely cited as the genericity construct that popularized the notion among programmers and language designers and supports many generic programming idioms.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The D language also offers fully generic-capable templates based on the C++ precedent but with a simplified syntax.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The Java language has provided genericity facilities syntactically based on C++'s since the introduction of Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] C# 2.0, Oxygene 1.5 (formerly Chrome) and Visual Basic (.NET) 2005 have constructs that exploit the support for generics present in Microsoft .NET Framework since version 2.0.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Ada has had generics since it was first designed in 1977–1980.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The standard library uses generics to provide many services.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Ada 2005 adds a comprehensive generic container library to the standard library, which was inspired by C++'s Standard Template Library.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A *generic unit* is a package or a subprogram that takes one or more *generic formal parameters*.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A *generic formal parameter* is a value, a variable, a constant, a type, a subprogram, or even an instance of another, designated, generic unit.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For generic formal types, the syntax distinguishes between discrete, floating-point, fixed-point, access (pointer) types, etc.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Some formal parameters can have default values.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] To *instantiate* a generic unit, the programmer passes *actual* parameters for each formal.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The generic instance then behaves just like any other unit.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] It is possible to instantiate generic units at run-time, for example, inside a loop.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The language syntax allows precise specification of constraints on generic formal parameters.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For example, it is possible to specify that a generic formal type will only accept a modular type as the actual.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] In this example, `Array_Type` is constrained by both `Index_Type` and `Element_Type`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] When instantiating the unit, the programmer must pass an actual array type that satisfies these constraints.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The disadvantage of this fine-grained control is a complicated syntax, but, because all generic formal parameters are completely defined in the specification, the compiler can instantiate generics without looking at the body of the generic.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Unlike C++, Ada does not allow specialised generic instances, and requires that all generics be instantiated explicitly.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] C++ uses templates to enable generic programming techniques.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The C++ Standard Library includes the Standard Template Library or STL that provides a framework of templates for common data structures and algorithms.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Templates in C++ may also be used for template metaprogramming, which is a way of pre-evaluating some of the code at compile-time rather than run-time.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Using template specialization, C++ Templates are Turing complete.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] There are many kinds of templates, the most common being function templates and class templates.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A *function template* is a pattern for creating ordinary functions based upon the parameterizing types supplied when instantiated.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For example, the C++ Standard Template Library contains the function template `std::max(x, y)` that creates functions that return either `x` or `y`, whichever is larger.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The compiler examines the arguments used to call `max` and determines that this is a call to `max(int, int)`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This works whether the arguments `x` and `y` are integers, strings, or any other type for which the expression `x < y` is sensible, or more specifically, for any type for which `operator<` is defined.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Common inheritance is not needed for the set of types that can be used, and so it is very similar to duck typing.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A program defining a custom data type can use operator overloading to define the meaning of `<` for that type, thus allowing its use with the `std::max()` function template.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] While this may seem a minor benefit in this isolated example, in the context of a comprehensive library like the STL it allows the programmer to get extensive functionality for a new data type, just by defining a few operators for it.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Merely defining `<` allows a type to be used with the standard `std::sort()`, `std::stable_sort()`, and `std::binary_search()` algorithms or to be put inside data structures such as `std::set<T>`s (equivalent to `TreeSet<T>`, heaps, and associative arrays.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] C++ templates are completely type safe at compile time.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] As a demonstration, the standard type `std::complex<T>` does not define the `<` operator, because there is no strict order on complex numbers.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Therefore, `std::max(x, y)` will fail with a compile error, if `x` and `y` are `complex` values.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Likewise, other templates that rely on `<` cannot be applied to `complex` data unless a comparison (in the form of a functor or function) is provided.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For instance, `std::complex<T>` cannot be used as key for a `std::map<K, V>` (equivalent to `TreeMap<K, V>`) unless a comparison is provided.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Unfortunately, compilers historically generate somewhat esoteric, long, and unhelpful error messages for this sort of error.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Ensuring that a certain object adheres to a method protocol can alleviate this issue.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Languages which use `std::compare` instead of `<` can also use `std::complex<T>` values as keys.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Another kind of template, a *class template*, extends the same concept to classes.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A class template specialization is a class.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Class templates are often used to make generic containers.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For example, the STL has a doubly linked list container, `std::list<T>` (equivalent to `LinkedList<T>`).
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] To make a linked list of integers, one writes `list<int>`, while a list of strings is denoted `list<string>`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A `std::list<T>` has a set of standard functions associated with it, that work for any compatible parameterizing types.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] C++20 introduces constraining template types using concepts.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A powerful feature of C++'s templates is *template specialization*.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This allows alternative implementations to be provided based on certain characteristics of the parameterized type that is being instantiated.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Template specialization has two purposes: to allow certain forms of optimization, and to reduce code bloat.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For example, consider a `sort()` template function.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] One of the primary activities that such a function does is to swap or exchange the values in two of the container's positions.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] If the values are large (in terms of the number of bytes it takes to store each of them), then it is often quicker to first build a separate list of pointers to the objects, sort those pointers, and then build the final sorted sequence.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] If the values are quite small however it is usually fastest to just swap the values in-place as needed.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Furthermore, if the parameterized type is already of some pointer-type, then there is no need to build a separate pointer array.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Template specialization allows the template creator to write different implementations and to specify the characteristics that the parameterized type(s) must have for each implementation to be used.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Unlike function templates, class templates can be partially specialized.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] That means that an alternate version of the class template code can be provided when some of the template parameters are known, while leaving other template parameters generic.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This can be used, for example, to create a default implementation (the *primary specialization*) that assumes that copying a parameterizing type is expensive and then create partial specializations for types that are cheap to copy, thus increasing overall efficiency.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Clients of such a class template just use specializations of it without needing to know whether the compiler used the primary specialization or some partial specialization in each case.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Class templates can also be *fully specialized,* which means that an alternate implementation can be provided when all of the parameterizing types are known.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Some uses of templates, such as the `max()` function, were formerly filled by function-like preprocessor macros (a legacy of the C language).
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Macros are expanded (copy pasted) by the preprocessor, before program compiling; templates are actual real functions.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Macros are always expanded inline; templates can also be inline functions when the compiler deems it appropriate.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] However, templates are generally considered an improvement over macros for these purposes.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Templates avoid some of the common errors found in code that makes heavy use of function-like macros, such as evaluating parameters with side effects twice.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Perhaps most importantly, templates were designed to be applicable to much larger problems than macros.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Many compilers historically had poor support for templates, thus the use of templates could make code somewhat less portable.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Support may also be poor when a C++ compiler is being used with a linker that is not C++-aware, or when attempting to use templates across shared library boundaries.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Compilers can produce confusing, long, and sometimes unhelpful error messages when errors are detected in code that uses SFINAE.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This can make templates difficult to develop with.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Finally, the use of templates requires the compiler to generate a separate *instance* of the templated class or function for every type parameters used with it.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] (This is necessary because types in C++ are not all the same size, and the sizes of data fields are important to how classes work.) So the indiscriminate use of templates can lead to code bloat, resulting in excessively large executables.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] However, judicious use of template specialization and derivation can dramatically reduce such code bloat in some cases:So, can derivation be used to reduce the problem of code replicated because templates are used?
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This would involve deriving a template from an ordinary class.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This technique proved successful in curbing code bloat in real use.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Templated classes or functions may require an *explicit specialization* of the template class which would require rewriting of an entire class for a specific template parameters used by it.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The extra instantiations generated by templates can also cause some debuggers to have difficulty working gracefully with templates.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For example, setting a debug breakpoint within a template from a source file may either miss setting the breakpoint in the actual instantiation desired or may set a breakpoint in every place the template is instantiated.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Also, the implementation source code for the template must be completely available (e.g. included in a header) to the translation unit (source file) using it.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Templates, including much of the Standard Library, if not included in header files, cannot be compiled.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] (This is in contrast to non-templated code, which may be compiled to binary, providing only a declarations header file for code using it.) This may be a disadvantage by exposing the implementing code, which removes some abstractions, and could restrict its use in closed-source projects.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The D language supports templates based in design on C++.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Templates in D use a different syntax than in C++: whereas in C++ template parameters are wrapped in angular brackets (`Template<param1, param2>`), D uses an exclamation sign and parentheses: `Template!(param1, param2)`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This avoids the C++ parsing difficulties due to ambiguity with comparison operators.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] If there is only one parameter, the parentheses can be omitted.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Conventionally, D combines the above features to provide compile-time polymorphism using trait-based generic programming.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Combining the above allows generating code based on existing declarations.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For example, D serialization frameworks can enumerate a type's members and generate specialized functions for each serialized type to perform serialization and deserialization.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] User-defined attributes could further indicate serialization rules.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The `import` expression and compile-time function execution also allow efficiently implementing domain-specific languages.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Generic classes have been a part of Eiffel since the original method and language design.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The foundation publications of Eiffel, use the term *genericity* to describe creating and using generic classes.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Generic classes are declared with their class name and a list of one or more *formal generic parameters*.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The formal generic parameters are placeholders for arbitrary class names that will be supplied when a declaration of the generic class is made, as shown in the two *generic derivations* below, where `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are other class names.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are considered *actual generic parameters* as they provide real class names to substitute for `G` in actual use.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Within the Eiffel type system, although class `LIST [G]` is considered a class, it is not considered a type.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] However, a generic derivation of `LIST [G]` such as `LIST [ACCOUNT]` is considered a type.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For the list class shown above, an actual generic parameter substituting for `G` can be any other available class.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] To constrain the set of classes from which valid actual generic parameters can be chosen, a *generic constraint* can be specified.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] In the declaration of class `SORTED_LIST` below, the generic constraint dictates that any valid actual generic parameter will be a class that inherits from class `COMPARABLE`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The generic constraint ensures that elements of a `SORTED_LIST` can in fact be sorted.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Support for the *generics*, or "containers-of-type-T" was added to the Java programming language in 2004 as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] In Java, generics are only checked at compile time for type correctness.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The generic type information is then removed via a process called type erasure, to maintain compatibility with old JVM implementations, making it unavailable at runtime.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For example, a `List<String>` is converted to the raw type `java.util.List`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The compiler inserts type casts to convert the elements to the `java.lang.String` type when they are retrieved from the list, reducing performance compared to other implementations such as C++ templates.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Generics were added as part of .NET Framework 2.0 in November 2005, based on a research prototype from Microsoft Research started in 1999.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Although similar to generics in Java, .NET generics do not apply type erasure, but implement generics as a first class mechanism in the runtime using reification.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This design choice provides additional functionality, such as allowing reflection with preservation of generic types, and alleviating some of the limits of erasure (such as being unable to create generic arrays).
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This also means that there is no performance hit from runtime casts and normally expensive boxing conversions.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] When primitive and value types are used as generic arguments, they get specialized implementations, allowing for efficient generic collections and methods.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] As in C++ and Java, nested generic types such as `Dictionary<string, List<int>>` are valid types, however are advised against for member signatures in code analysis design rules.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] .NET allows six varieties of generic type constraints using the `where` keyword including restricting generic types to be value types, to be classes, to have constructors, and to implement interfaces.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The `MakeAtLeast()` method allows operation on arrays, with elements of generic type `T`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The method's type constraint indicates that the method is applicable to any type `T` that implements the generic `System.IComparable<T>` interface.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This ensures a compile time error, if the method is called if the type does not support comparison.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The interface provides the generic method `CompareTo(T)`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The above method could also be written without generic types, simply using the non-generic `System.Array` type.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] However, since arrays are contravariant, the casting would not be type safe, and the compiler would be unable to find certain possible errors that would otherwise be caught when using generic types.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] In addition, the method would need to access the array items as `object`s instead, and would require casting to compare two elements.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A notable behavior of static members in a generic .NET class is static member instantiation per run-time type (see example below).
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] For Pascal, generics were first implemented in 2006, in the implementation Free Pascal.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The Object Pascal dialect Delphi acquired generics in the 2007 Delphi 11 release by CodeGear, initially only with the .NET compiler (since discontinued) before being added to the native code in the 2009 Delphi 12 release.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The semantics and abilities of Delphi generics are largely modelled on those of generics in .NET 2.0, though the implementation is by necessity quite different.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] As with C#, methods and whole types can have one or more type parameters.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] In the example, TArray is a generic type (defined by the language) and MakeAtLeast a generic method.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The available constraints are very similar to the available constraints in C#: any value type, any class, a specific class or interface, and a class with a parameterless constructor.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Multiple constraints act as an additive union.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Free Pascal implemented generics in 2006 in version 2.2.0, before Delphi and with different syntax and semantics.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] However, since FPC version 2.6.0, the Delphi-style syntax is available when using the language mode `{$mode Delphi}`.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Thus, Free Pascal code supports generics in either style.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The type class mechanism of Haskell supports generic programming.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] All the necessary methods will be "derived" – that is, constructed automatically – based on the structure of the type.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] This results in an equality function (`==`) and a string representation function (`show`) being automatically defined for any type of the form `BinTree T` provided that `T` itself supports those operations.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Ralf Hinze (2004) has shown that a similar effect can be achieved for user-defined type classes by certain programming techniques.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Other researchers have proposed approaches to this and other kinds of genericity in the context of Haskell and extensions to Haskell (discussed below).
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] PolyP was the first generic programming language extension to Haskell.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] In PolyP, generic functions are called *polytypic*.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The language introduces a special construct in which such polytypic functions can be defined via structural induction over the structure of the pattern functor of a regular datatype.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Regular datatypes in PolyP are a subset of Haskell datatypes.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A regular datatype t must be of kind ** → **, and if *a* is the formal type argument in the definition, then all recursive calls to *t* must have the form *t a*.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] These restrictions rule out higher-kinded datatypes and nested datatypes, where the recursive calls are of a different form.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Generic Haskell is another extension to Haskell, developed at Utrecht University in the Netherlands.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] The resulting type-indexed value can be specialized to any type.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Clean offers generic programming based PolyP and the Generic Haskell as supported by the GHC ≥ 6.0.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] It parametrizes by kind as those but offers overloading.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Languages in the ML family support generic programming through parametric polymorphism and generic modules called *functors.* Both Standard ML and OCaml provide functors, which are similar to class templates and to Ada's generic packages.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Scheme syntactic abstractions also have a connection to genericity – these are in fact a superset of C++ templates.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] A Verilog module may take one or more parameters, to which their actual values are assigned upon the instantiation of the module.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] One example is a generic register array where the array width is given via a parameter.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Such an array, combined with a generic wire vector, can make a generic buffer or memory module with an arbitrary bit width out of a single module implementation.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] VHDL, being derived from Ada, also has generic abilities.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] C has a feature called "type-generic expressions" using the `_Generic` keyword: This feature gives C function overloading capabilities, but is not related to generic programming.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Generic programming can be achieved by using the preprocessor to define the generic code, with macro expansion taking the role of *instantiation*.
[src:fortress-language/generic-programming] Sometimes, the non-standard extension "statement expressions" is used to simulate function-like behaviour for generic code.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Steele was born in Missouri and graduated from the Boston Latin School in 1972.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] He received a Bachelor of Arts (BA) in applied mathematics from Harvard University (1975) and a Master's degree (MS) and Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) from Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) in computer science (1977, 1980).
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] He then worked as an assistant professor of computer science at Carnegie Mellon University and a compiler implementer at Tartan Laboratories.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Then he joined the supercomputer company Thinking Machines, where he helped define and promote a parallel computing version of the Lisp programming language named *Lisp (Star Lisp) and a parallel version of the language C named C*.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] In 1994, Steele joined Sun Microsystems and was invited by Bill Joy to become a member of the Java team after the language had been designed, since he had a track record of writing good specifications for extant languages.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Steele joined Oracle in 2010 when Oracle acquired Sun Microsystems.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] While at MIT, Steele published more than two dozen papers with Gerald Jay Sussman on the subject of the language Lisp and its implementation (the Lambda Papers).
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] One of their most notable contributions was the design of the language Scheme.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Steele also designed the original command set of Emacs and was the first to port TeX (from WAITS to ITS).
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] He has published papers on other subjects, including compilers, parallel processing, and constraint languages.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] One song he composed has been published in the official journal of the Association for Computing Machinery *Communications of the ACM* (CACM) ("The Telnet Song", April 1984, a parody of the behavior of a series of PDP-10 TELNET implementations written by Mark Crispin).
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] He was also a member of the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE) working group that produced the IEEE Standard for the language Scheme, IEEE Std 1178–1990.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] He represented Sun Microsystems in the High Performance Fortran Forum, which produced the High Performance Fortran specification in May, 1993.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] In addition to specifications of the language Java, Steele's work at Sun Microsystems has included research in parallel algorithms, implementation strategies, and architecture and software support.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] In 2005, Steele began leading a team of researchers at Sun developing a new language named Fortress, a high-performance language designed to obsolete Fortran.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Steele participated in the development of the Verse programming language designed by Epic Games.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] In 1982, Steele edited *The Hacker's Dictionary* (Harper & Row, 1983; ISBN 0-06-091082-8), which was a print version of the Jargon File.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Harbison wrote *C: A Reference Manual*, (Prentice-Hall, 1984; ISBN 0-13-110016-5), to provide a precise description of the language C, which Tartan Laboratories was trying to implement on a wide range of systems.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Both authors participated in the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) C standardization process; several revisions of the book were issued to reflect the new standard.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] On 16 March 1984, Steele published *Common Lisp the Language* (Digital Press; ISBN 0-932376-41-X; 465 pages).
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] This first edition was the original specification of Common Lisp (CLtL1) and served as the basis for the ANSI standard.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Steele released a greatly expanded second edition in 1990, (1029 pages) which documented a near-final version of the ANSI standard.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Zosel wrote *The High Performance Fortran Handbook* (MIT Press, 1994; ISBN 0-262-11185-3).
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Steele also coauthored the original *The Java Language Specification* with James Gosling and Bill Joy.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Steele received the ACM Grace Murray Hopper Award in 1988.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] He was named a Founding AAAI Fellow in 1990, an ACM Fellow in 1994, a member of the National Academy of Engineering of the United States of America in 2001 and a Fellow of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 2002.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Dobb's Excellence in Programming Award in 2005.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] He was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society in 2026.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Steele is a modern western square dancer and caller from Mainstream up through C3A, a member of Tech Squares, and a member of Callerlab.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] Under the pseudonym *Great Quux*, which was an old student nickname at the Boston Latin School and MIT, he has published light verse and "Crunchly" cartoons; a few of the latter appeared in *The New Hacker's Dictionary*.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] In 1998, Steele solved the game Teeko via computer, showing what must occur if both players play wisely; he found that neither player can force a win.
[src:fortress-language/guy-l-steele-jr] He also showed that the Advanced Teeko variant is a win for Black (again, assuming perfect play), as is one other variant, but the other fourteen variants are draws.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates systems administration (including network and security knowledge), parallel computing and distributed computing into a multidisciplinary field that combines digital electronics, computer architecture, system software, programming languages, algorithms and computational techniques.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] HPC technologies are the tools and systems used to implement and create high performance computing systems.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Since around 2005, HPC systems have shifted from supercomputing to computing clusters and grids.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Because of the need of networking in clusters and grids, High Performance Computing Technologies are achieved by the use of a collapsed network backbone, because the collapsed backbone architecture is simple to troubleshoot and upgrades can be applied to a single router as opposed to multiple ones.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] HPC integrates with data analytics in AI engineering workflows to generate new data streams that increase a simulation's ability to answer the "what if" questions.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] The term is most commonly associated with computing used for scientific research or computational science.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] A related term, high-performance technical computing (HPTC), generally refers to the engineering applications of cluster-based computing (such as computational fluid dynamics and the building and testing of virtual prototypes).
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] HPC has also been applied to business uses such as data warehouses, line of business (LOB) applications, and transaction processing.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] High-performance computing (HPC) as a term arose after the term "supercomputing".
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] HPC is sometimes used as a synonym for supercomputing; but, in other contexts, "supercomputer" is used to refer to a more powerful subset of "high-performance computers", and the term "supercomputing" becomes a subset of "high-performance computing".
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] The potential for confusion over the use of these terms is apparent.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Because most current applications are not designed for HPC technologies but are retrofitted, they are not designed or tested for scaling to more powerful processors or machines.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Since networking clusters and grids use multiple processors and computers, these scaling problems can cripple critical systems in future supercomputing systems.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Therefore, either the existing tools do not address the needs of the high performance computing community or the HPC community is unaware of these tools.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] In government and research institutions, scientists simulate galaxy formation and evolution, fusion energy, and global warming, as well as work to create more accurate short- and long-term weather forecasts.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] The world's tenth most powerful supercomputer in 2008, IBM Roadrunner (located at the United States Department of Energy's Los Alamos National Laboratory) simulated the performance, safety, and reliability of nuclear weapons and certifies their functionality.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] TOP500 ranks the world's 500 fastest high-performance computers, as measured by the High Performance LINPACK (HPL) benchmark.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Not all existing computers are ranked, either because they are ineligible (e.g., they cannot run the HPL benchmark) or because their owners have not submitted an HPL score (e.g., because they do not wish the size of their system to become public information, for defense reasons).
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] In addition, the use of the single LINPACK benchmark is controversial, in that no single measure can test all aspects of a high-performance computer.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] To help overcome the limitations of the LINPACK test, the U.S. government commissioned one of its originators, Jack Dongarra of the University of Tennessee, to create a suite of benchmark tests that includes LINPACK and others, called the HPC Challenge benchmark suite.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] This evolving suite has been used in some HPC procurements, but, because it is not reducible to a single number, it has been unable to overcome the publicity advantage of the less useful TOP500 LINPACK test.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] The TOP500 list is updated twice a year, once in June at the ISC European Supercomputing Conference and again at a US Supercomputing Conference in November.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Many ideas for the new wave of grid computing were originally borrowed from HPC.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Traditionally, HPC has involved an on-premises infrastructure, investing in supercomputers or computer clusters.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Over the last decade, cloud computing has grown in popularity for offering computer resources in the commercial sector regardless of their investment capabilities.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] Some characteristics like scalability and containerization also have raised interest in academia.
[src:fortress-language/high-performance-computing] However security in the cloud concerns such as data confidentiality are still considered when deciding between cloud or on-premise HPC resources.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:fortress-language/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun products included computer servers and workstations built using Motorola 680x0 processors, then later their own RISC-based SPARC processor architecture, as well as on x86-based AMD Opteron and Intel Xeon processors.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun also developed its own storage systems and a suite of software products, including the Unix-based SunOS and later Solaris operating systems, developer tools, Web infrastructure software, and identity management applications.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Technologies that Sun created include the Java programming language, the Java platform and Network File System (NFS).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In general, Sun was a proponent of open systems, particularly Unix.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It was also a major contributor to open-source software, as evidenced by its $1 billion purchase, in 2008, of MySQL, an open-source relational database management system.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Other notable Sun acquisitions include Cray Business Systems Division, Storagetek, and Innotek GmbH, creators of VirtualBox.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] On April 20, 2009, it was announced that Oracle would acquire Sun for US$7.4 billion, or US$5.6 billion net of Sun's cash and debt.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The deal was completed on January 27, 2010.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The initial design for what became Sun's first Unix workstation, the Sun-1, was conceived by Andy Bechtolsheim when he was a graduate student at Stanford University in Palo Alto, California.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Bechtolsheim originally designed the SUN workstation for the Stanford University Network communications project as a personal CAD workstation.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It was designed around the Motorola 68000 processor with an advanced memory management unit (MMU) to support the Unix operating system with virtual memory support.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] He built the first examples from spare parts obtained from Stanford's Department of Computer Science and Silicon Valley supply houses.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] On February 24, 1982, Scott McNealy, Andy Bechtolsheim, and Vinod Khosla, all Stanford graduate students, founded *Sun Microsystems*.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Bill Joy of Berkeley, a primary developer of the Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD), joined soon after and is counted as one of the original founders.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The company was the second, after rival Apollo Computer, to specialize in workstations.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The name "Sun" is derived from the initials of the Stanford University Network (SUN).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] McNealy focused on operations; *Fortune* described him as "notoriously cheap".
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun was profitable from its first quarter in July 1982.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] By 1983, Sun was known for producing 68k-based systems with high-quality graphics that were the only computers other than DEC's VAX to run 4.2BSD.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It licensed the computer design to other manufacturers, which typically used it to build Multibus-based systems running Unix from UniSoft.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Wall Street was an important early market, as were CAD/CAM, CAE, CASE, and other technical markets.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] By 1989, *InfoWorld* described Sun as "the unqualified leader in the workstation arena", and target of DEC and Hewlett-Packard (HP)'s own products.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's initial public offering was in 1986 under the stock symbol *SUNW*, for *Sun Workstations* (later *Sun Worldwide*).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The symbol was changed in 2007 to *JAVA*; Sun stated that the brand awareness associated with its Java platform better represented the company's current strategy.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's logo, which features four interleaved copies of the word *sun* in the form of a rotationally symmetric ambigram, was designed by professor Vaughan Pratt, also of Stanford.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The initial version of the logo was orange and had the sides oriented horizontally and vertically, but it was subsequently rotated to stand on one corner and re-colored purple, and later blue.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] During the dot-com bubble, Sun began making more money, with its stock rising as high as $250 per share.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It also began spending much more, hiring workers and building itself out.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Some of this was because of genuine demand, but much was from web start-up companies anticipating business that would never happen.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sales in Sun's important hardware division went into freefall as customers closed shop and auctioned high-end servers.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Several quarters of steep losses led to executive departures, rounds of layoffs, and other cost cutting.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In December 2001, the stock fell to the 1998, pre-bubble level of about $100.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It continued to fall, faster than many other technology companies.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] A year later, it had reached below $10 (a tenth of what it was in 1990), but it eventually bounced back to $20.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In mid-2004, Sun closed its Newark, California, factory and consolidated all manufacturing to Hillsboro, Oregon and Linlithgow, Scotland.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2006, the rest of the Newark campus was put on the market.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2004, Sun canceled two major processor projects which emphasized high instruction-level parallelism and operating frequency.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Instead, the company chose to concentrate on processors optimized for multi-threading and multiprocessing, such as the UltraSPARC T1 processor (codenamed "Niagara").
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The company also announced a collaboration with Fujitsu to use the Japanese company's processor chips in mid-range and high-end Sun servers.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] These servers were announced on April 17, 2007, as the M-Series, part of the SPARC Enterprise series.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In February 2005, Sun announced the Sun Grid, a grid computing deployment on which it offered utility computing services priced at US$1 per CPU/hour for processing and per GB/month for storage.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] This offering built upon an existing 3,000-CPU server farm used for internal R&D for over 10 years, which Sun marketed as being able to achieve 97% utilization.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In August 2005, the first commercial use of this grid was announced for financial risk simulations which were later launched as its first software as a service product.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In January 2005, Sun reported a net profit of $19 million for fiscal 2005 second quarter, for the first time in three years.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] This was followed by net loss of $9 million on GAAP basis for the third quarter 2005, as reported on April 14, 2005.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In January 2007, Sun reported a net GAAP profit of $126 million on revenue of $3.337 billion for its fiscal second quarter.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Shortly following that news, it was announced that Kohlberg Kravis Roberts (KKR) would invest $700 million in the company.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun had engineering groups in Bangalore, Beijing, Dublin, Grenoble, Hamburg, Prague, St.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Petersburg, Tel Aviv, Tokyo, Canberra and Trondheim.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2007–2008, Sun posted revenue of $13.8 billion and had $2 billion in cash.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] First-quarter 2008 losses were $1.68 billion; revenue fell 7% to $12.99 billion.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's stock lost 80% of its value November 2007 to November 2008, reducing the company's market value to $3 billion.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] With falling sales to large corporate clients, Sun announced plans to lay off 5,000 to 6,000 workers, or 15–18% of its work force.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It expected to save $700 million to $800 million a year as a result of the moves, while also taking up to $600 million in charges.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] On September 3, 2009, the European Commission opened an in-depth investigation into the proposed takeover of Sun Microsystems by Oracle.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] On November 9, 2009, the Commission issued a statement of objections relating to the acquisition.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Finally, on January 21, 2010, the European Commission approved Oracle's acquisition of Sun.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The Commission's investigation showed that another open database, PostgreSQL, was considered by many users of this type of software as a credible alternative to MySQL and could to some extent replace the competitive strength that the latter currently represents in the database market.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun was sold to Oracle Corporation in 2009 for $5.6 billion.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's staff were asked to share anecdotes about their experiences at Sun.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] A website containing videos, stories, and photographs from 27 years at Sun was made available on September 2, 2009.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In October, Sun announced a second round of thousands of employees to be laid off, blamed partially on delays in approval of the merger.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The transaction was completed in early 2010.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In January 2011, Oracle agreed to pay $46 million to settle charges that it submitted false claims to US federal government agencies and paid "kickbacks" to systems integrators.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In February 2011, Sun's former Menlo Park, California, campus of about 1,000,000 square feet (93,000 m2) was sold, and it was announced that it would become headquarters for Facebook.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The sprawling facility, built around an enclosed courtyard, was nicknamed "Sun Quentin" by Facebook's employees.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Notably, Facebook founder Mark Zuckerberg did not change the sign in the front of the campus, he simply had it turned around and the company's logo put on the other side.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] On September 1, 2011, Sun India legally became part of Oracle.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It had been delayed due to legal issues in Indian court.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] As of May 11, 2009, the following shareholders held over 100,000 common shares of Sun and at $9.50 per share offered by Oracle, they received the amounts indicated when the acquisition closed.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] For the first decade of Sun's history, the company positioned its products as technical workstations, competing successfully as a low-cost vendor during the Workstation Wars of the 1980s.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It then shifted its hardware product line to emphasize servers and storage.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] High-level telecom control systems such as Operational Support Systems service predominantly used Sun equipment.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun originally used Motorola 68000 family central processing units for the Sun-1 through Sun-3 computer series.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The Sun-3 series was based on the 68020, with the later Sun-3x using the 68030.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 1987, the company began using *SPARC (Scalable Processor ARChitecture)*, a RISC processor architecture of its own design, in its computer systems, starting with the Sun-4 line.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] SPARC was initially a 32-bit architecture (SPARC V7) until the introduction of the SPARC V9 architecture in 1995, which added 64-bit extensions.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun developed several generations of SPARC-based computer systems, including the SPARCstation, Ultra, and Sun Blade series of workstations, and the SPARCserver, Netra, Enterprise, and Sun Fire line of servers.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In the early 1990s the company began to extend its product line to include large-scale symmetric multiprocessing servers, starting with the four-processor SPARCserver 600MP.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] This was followed by the 8-processor SPARCserver 1000 and 20-processor SPARCcenter 2000, which were based on work done in conjunction with Xerox PARC.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 1995 the company introduced Sun Ultra series machines that were equipped with the first 64-bit implementation of SPARC processors (UltraSPARC).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In the late 1990s the transformation of product line in favor of large 64-bit SMP systems was accelerated by the acquisition of Cray Business Systems Division from Silicon Graphics.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Their 32-bit, 64-processor Cray Superserver 6400, related to the SPARCcenter, led to the 64-bit Sun Enterprise 10000 high-end server (otherwise known as *Starfire* or E10K).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In September 2004, Sun made available systems with UltraSPARC IV which was the first multi-core SPARC processor.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It was followed by UltraSPARC IV+ in September 2005 and its revisions with higher clock speeds in 2007.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] These CPUs were used in the most powerful, enterprise class high-end CC-NUMA servers developed by Sun, such as the Sun Fire E15K and the Sun Fire E25K.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In November 2005, Sun launched the UltraSPARC T1, notable for its ability to concurrently run 32 threads of execution on 8 processor cores.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Its intent was to drive more efficient use of CPU resources, which is of particular importance in data centers, where there is an increasing need to reduce power and air conditioning demands, much of which comes from the heat generated by CPUs.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The T1 was followed in 2007 by the UltraSPARC T2, which extended the number of threads per core from 4 to 8.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun has open sourced the design specifications of both the T1 and T2 processors via the OpenSPARC project.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2006, Sun ventured into the *blade server* (high density rack-mounted systems) market with the Sun Blade (distinct from the Sun Blade workstation).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In April 2007, Sun released the SPARC Enterprise server products, jointly designed by Sun and Fujitsu and based on Fujitsu SPARC64 VI and later processors.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The *M-class* SPARC Enterprise systems include high-end reliability and availability features.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Later T-series servers have also been badged SPARC Enterprise rather than Sun Fire.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In April 2008, Sun released servers with UltraSPARC T2 Plus, which is an SMP capable version of UltraSPARC T2, available in 2 or 4 processor configurations.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It was the first CoolThreads CPU with multi-processor capability and it made possible to build standard rack-mounted servers that could simultaneously process up to massive 256 CPU threads in hardware (Sun SPARC Enterprise T5440), which is considered a record in the industry.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Since 2010, all further development of Sun machines based on SPARC architecture (including new SPARC T-Series servers, SPARC T3 and T4 chips) is done as a part of Oracle Corporation hardware division.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In the late 1980s, Sun also marketed an Intel 80386–based machine, the Sun386i; this was designed to be a hybrid system, running SunOS but at the same time supporting DOS applications.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] This only remained on the market for a brief time.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] A follow-up "486i" upgrade was announced but only a few prototype units were ever manufactured.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's brief first foray into x86 systems ended in the early 1990s, as it decided to concentrate on SPARC and retire the last Motorola systems and 386i products, a move dubbed by McNealy as "all the wood behind one arrowhead".
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Even so, Sun kept its hand in the x86 world, as a release of Solaris for PC compatibles began shipping in 1993.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 1997, Sun acquired Diba, Inc., followed later by the acquisition of Cobalt Networks in 2000, with the aim of building *network appliances* (single function computers meant for consumers).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun also marketed a Network Computer (a term popularized and eventually trademarked by Oracle); the JavaStation was a diskless system designed to run Java applications.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Although none of these business initiatives were particularly successful, the Cobalt purchase gave Sun a toehold for its return to the x86 hardware market.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2002, Sun introduced its first general purpose x86 system, the LX50, based in part on previous Cobalt system expertise.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] This was also Sun's first system announced to support Linux as well as Solaris.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2003, Sun announced a strategic alliance with AMD to produce x86/x64 servers based on AMD's Opteron processor; this was followed shortly by Sun's acquisition of Kealia, a startup founded by original Sun founder Andy Bechtolsheim, which had been focusing on high-performance AMD-based servers.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The following year, Sun launched the Opteron-based Sun Fire V20z and V40z servers, and the Sun Java Workstation W1100z and W2100z workstations.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In September 2005 Sun unveiled a new range of Opteron-based servers: the Sun Fire X2100, X4100 and X4200 servers.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] These were designed from scratch by a team led by Bechtolsheim to address heat and power consumption issues commonly faced in data centers.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In July 2006, the Sun Fire X4500 and X4600 systems were introduced, extending a line of x64 systems that support not only Solaris, but also Linux and Microsoft Windows.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In January 2007 Sun announced a broad strategic alliance with Intel.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Intel endorsed Solaris as a mainstream operating system and as its mission critical Unix for its Xeon processor–based systems, and contributed engineering resources to OpenSolaris.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun began using the Intel Xeon processor in its x64 server line, starting with the Sun Blade X6250 server module introduced in June 2007.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In May 2008 AMD announced its Operating System Research Center (OSRC) was expanding its focus to include optimization to Sun's OpenSolaris and xVM virtualization products for AMD processors.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Although Sun was initially known as a hardware company, its software history began with its founding in 1982; co-founder Bill Joy was one of the leading Unix developers of the time, having contributed the vi editor, the C shell, and significant work developing TCP/IP and the BSD Unix OS.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun later developed software such as the Java programming language and acquired software such as StarOffice, VirtualBox and MySQL.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In February 1991, the company established SunSoft, Inc., a wholly owned division of Sun dedicated to the development of operating systems and application software.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun used community-based and open-source licensing of its major technologies, and for its support of its products with other open source technologies.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] GNOME-based desktop software called Java Desktop System (originally code-named "Madhatter") was distributed for the Solaris operating system, and at one point for Linux.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun supported its Java Enterprise System (a middleware stack) on Linux.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It released the source code for Solaris under the open-source Common Development and Distribution License, via the OpenSolaris community.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's positioning includes a commitment to indemnify users of some software from intellectual property disputes concerning that software.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] It offers support services on a variety of pricing bases, including per-employee and per-socket.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] A 2006 report prepared for the EU by UNU-MERIT stated that Sun was the largest corporate contributor to open source movements in the world.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] According to this report, Sun's open source contributions exceed the combined total of the next five largest commercial contributors.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun is best known for its Unix systems, which have a reputation for system stability and a consistent design philosophy.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's first workstation shipped with UniSoft V7 Unix.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Later in 1982 Sun began providing SunOS, a customized 4.2BSD Unix, as the operating system for its workstations.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] SunOS included suntools, an early GUI window system.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In the late 1980s, AT&T tapped Sun to help them develop the next release of their branded UNIX, and in 1988 announced they would purchase up to a 20% stake in Sun.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] UNIX System V Release 4 (SVR4) was jointly developed by AT&T and Sun.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun used SVR4 as the foundation for Solaris 2.x, which became the successor to SunOS 4.1.x (later retroactively named Solaris 1.x).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] By the mid-1990s, the ensuing Unix wars had largely subsided, AT&T had sold off its Unix interests, and the relationship between the two companies was significantly reduced.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Dougherty, founder of Berkeley Softworks (which would go on to be re-incorporated as the *GeoWorks Corporation*) accused the Java development team at Sun for studying GeoWorks's PC/GEOS operating system and incorporating features of PC/GEOS into their Unix-based operating system.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Brian claimed that the object-oriented and flexible UI of PC/GEOS was "to this day the most sophisticated UI technology ever built into an OS".
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] From 1992 Sun also sold Interactive Unix, an operating system it acquired when it bought Interactive Systems Corporation from Eastman Kodak Company.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] This was a popular Unix variant for the PC platform and a major competitor to market leader SCO UNIX.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's focus on Interactive Unix diminished in favor of Solaris on both SPARC and x86 systems; it was dropped as a product in 2001.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun dropped the Solaris 2.x version numbering scheme after the Solaris 2.6 release (1997); the following version was branded Solaris 7.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] This was the first 64-bit release, intended for the new UltraSPARC CPUs based on the SPARC V9 architecture.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Within the next four years, the successors Solaris 8 and Solaris 9 were released in 2000 and 2002 respectively.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Following several years of difficult competition and loss of server market share to competitors' Linux-based systems, Sun began to include Linux as part of its strategy in 2002.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun supported both Red Hat Enterprise Linux and SUSE Linux Enterprise Server on its x64 systems; companies such as Canonical Ltd., Wind River Systems and MontaVista also supported their versions of Linux on Sun's SPARC-based systems.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2004, after having cultivated a reputation as one of Microsoft's most vocal antagonists, Sun entered into a joint relationship with them, resolving various legal entanglements between the two companies and receiving US$1.95 billion in settlement payments from them.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun supported Microsoft Windows on its x64 systems, and announced other collaborative agreements with Microsoft, including plans to support each other's virtualization environments.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2005, the company released Solaris 10.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The new version included a large number of enhancements to the operating system, as well as very novel features, previously unseen in the industry.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Solaris 10 update releases continued through the next 8 years, the last release from Sun Microsystems being Solaris 10 10/09.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The following updates were released by Oracle under the new license agreement; the final release is Solaris 10 1/13.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Previously, Sun offered a separate variant of Solaris called Trusted Solaris, which included augmented security features such as multilevel security and a least privilege access model.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Solaris 10 included many of the same capabilities as Trusted Solaris at the time of its initial release; Solaris 10 11/06 included Solaris Trusted Extensions, which give it the remaining capabilities needed to make it the functional successor to Trusted Solaris.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] After the release of Solaris 10, the Solaris source code was opened under the CDDL free software license and developed in open with contributing Opensolaris community through SXCE that used SVR4 .pkg packaging and supported OpenSolaris releases that used IPS.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Following the acquisition of Sun by Oracle, OpenSolaris continued to develop in open under illumos with illumos distributions.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Oracle Corporation continued to develop Solaris, reverting new development back to the proprietary licensing; its next release was Oracle Solaris 11 in November 2011.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The Java platform was developed at Sun by James Gosling in the early 1990s with the objective of allowing programs to function regardless of the device they were used on, sparking the slogan "Write once, run anywhere" (WORA).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] While this objective was not entirely achieved (prompting the riposte "Write once, debug everywhere"), Java is regarded as being largely hardware—and operating system—independent.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Java was initially promoted as a platform for client-side *applets* running inside web browsers.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Early examples of Java applications were the HotJava web browser and the HotJava Views suite.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] However, since then Java has been more successful on the server side of the Internet.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The platform consists of three major parts: the Java programming language, the Java Virtual Machine (JVM), and several Java Application Programming Interfaces (APIs).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The design of the Java platform is controlled by the vendor and user community through the Java Community Process (JCP).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Java is an object-oriented programming language.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Since its introduction in late 1995, it became one of the world's most popular programming languages.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Java programs are compiled to bytecode, which can be executed by any JVM, regardless of the environment.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The Java APIs provide an extensive set of library routines.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] On November 13, 2006, Sun announced it would be licensing its Java implementation under the GNU General Public License; it released its Java compiler and JVM at that time.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In February 2009, Sun entered a battle with Microsoft and Adobe Systems, which promoted rival platforms to build software applications for the Internet.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] JavaFX was a development platform for music, video and other applications that builds on the Java programming language.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 1999, Sun acquired the German software company Star Division and with it the office suite StarOffice, which Sun later released as OpenOffice.org under both GNU LGPL and the SISSL (Sun Industry Standards Source License).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] OpenOffice.org supported Microsoft Office file formats (though not perfectly), was available on many platforms (primarily Linux, Microsoft Windows, Mac OS X, and Solaris) and was used in the open source community.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] StarOffice also contained commercially licensed functions and add-ons; in OpenOffice.org these were either replaced by open-source or free variants, or are not present at all.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Both packages had native support for the OpenDocument format.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Derivatives of OpenOffice.org continue to be developed, such as LibreOffice, Collabora Online and Apache OpenOffice.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2007, Sun announced the Sun xVM virtualization and datacenter automation product suite for commodity hardware.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Earlier virtualization technologies from Sun like *Dynamic System Domains* and *Dynamic Reconfiguration* were specifically designed for high-end SPARC servers, and Logical Domains only supports the UltraSPARC T1/T2/T2 Plus server platforms.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun marketed *Sun Ops Center* provisioning software for datacenter automation.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] On the client side, Sun offered virtual desktop solutions.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Desktop environments and applications could be hosted in a datacenter, with users accessing these environments from a wide range of client devices, including Microsoft Windows PCs, Sun Ray virtual display clients, Apple Macintoshes, PDAs or any combination of supported devices.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] A variety of networks were supported, from LAN to WAN or the public Internet.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Virtual desktop products included Sun Ray Server Software, Sun Secure Global Desktop and Sun Virtual Desktop Infrastructure.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun acquired MySQL AB, the developer of the MySQL database in 2008 for US$1 billion.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] CEO Jonathan Schwartz mentioned in his blog that optimizing the performance of MySQL was one of the priorities of the acquisition.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In February 2008, Sun began to publish results of the MySQL performance optimization work.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun contributed to the PostgreSQL project.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] On the Java platform, Sun contributed to and supported Java DB.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun offered other software products for software development and infrastructure services.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Many were developed in house; others came from acquisitions, including Tarantella, Waveset Technologies, SeeBeyond, and Vaau.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun acquired many of the Netscape non-browser software products as part a deal involving Netscape's merger with AOL.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] These software products were initially offered under the "iPlanet" brand; once the Sun-Netscape alliance ended, they were re-branded as "Sun ONE" (Sun Open Network Environment), and then the "Sun Java System".
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's middleware product was branded as the *Java Enterprise System* (JES), and marketed for web and application serving, communication, calendaring, directory, identity management and service-oriented architecture.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun's Open ESB and other software suites were available free of charge on systems running Solaris, Red Hat Enterprise Linux, HP-UX, and Windows, with support available optionally.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun developed data center management software products, which included the *Solaris Cluster* high availability software, and a grid management package called *Sun Grid Engine* and firewall software such as SunScreen.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] For Network Equipment Providers and telecommunications customers, Sun developed the Sun Netra High-Availability Suite.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun produced compilers and development tools under the *Sun Studio* brand, for building and developing Solaris and Linux applications.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun entered the software as a service (SaaS) market with zembly, a social cloud-based computing platform and Project Kenai, an open-source project hosting service.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun sold its own storage systems to complement its system offerings; it has also made several storage-related acquisitions.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] On June 2, 2005, Sun announced it would purchase Storage Technology Corporation (StorageTek) for US$4.1 billion in cash, or $37.00 per share, a deal completed in August 2005.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2006, Sun introduced the Sun StorageTek 5800 System, the first application-aware programmable storage solution.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2008, Sun contributed the source code of the StorageTek 5800 System under the BSD license.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun announced the Sun Open Storage platform in 2008 built with open source technologies.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In late 2008 Sun announced the Sun Storage 7000 Unified Storage systems (codenamed Amber Road).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Transparent placement of data in the systems' solid-state drives (SSD) and conventional hard drives was managed by ZFS to take advantage of the speed of SSDs and the economy of conventional hard disks.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Other storage products included Sun Fire X4500 storage server and SAM-QFS filesystem and storage management software.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun marketed the Sun Constellation System for high-performance computing (HPC).
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] The *Sun HPC ClusterTools* product was a set of Message Passing Interface (MPI) libraries and tools for running parallel jobs on Solaris HPC clusters.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Beginning with version 7.0, Sun switched from its own implementation of MPI to Open MPI, and donated engineering resources to the Open MPI project.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun was a participant in the OpenMP language committee.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun Studio compilers and tools implemented the OpenMP specification for shared memory parallelization.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2006, Sun built the *TSUBAME supercomputer*, which was until June 2008 the fastest supercomputer in Asia.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun built *Ranger* at the Texas Advanced Computing Center (TACC) in 2007.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Ranger had a peak performance of over 500 TFLOPS, and was the sixth-most-powerful supercomputer on the TOP500 list in November 2008.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun announced an OpenSolaris distribution that integrated Sun's HPC products with others.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Notable Sun employees included John Gilmore, Whitfield Diffie, Radia Perlman, Ivan Sutherland, Marc Tremblay, and Satya Nadella.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun was an early advocate of Unix-based networked computing, promoting TCP/IP and especially NFS, as reflected in the company's motto The Network is the Computer, coined by John Gage.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] James Gosling led the team which developed the Java programming language.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Jon Bosak led the creation of the XML specification at W3C.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] In 2005, Sun Microsystems was one of the first Fortune 500 companies that instituted a formal social media program.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Sun staff published articles on the company's blog site.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Staff were encouraged to use the site to blog on any aspect of their work or personal life, with few restrictions placed on staff, other than commercially confidential material.
[src:fortress-language/sun-microsystems] Schwartz was one of the first CEOs of large companies to regularly blog; his postings were frequently quoted and analyzed in the press.
